    <!-- ============================================
         THE CALL
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="call">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🗺️</span> The Call as Creation Strategy</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        "Go from your country… and I will make you into a great nation, and I will bless you; I will make your name great, and you will be a blessing… and all the families of the earth will be blessed through you."
        <span class="reference">Genesis 12:1–3</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Genesis 12 opens with a hinge so abrupt it is easy to miss its logic. Eleven chapters have diagnosed a broken world; now God speaks two words to a childless man in a moon-worshiping city: <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">לֶךְ־לְךָ</span> (<em>lekh lekha</em>) — "go." The call of Abram is not a change of subject from Genesis 1–11. It is God's answer to it.</p>
      <p>The literary seams make the connection first. Genesis 11 closes with the cycle's darkest beat yet: the ten-generation genealogy from Shem narrows to Terah's family, and the unit is composed as de-creation by <em>death</em> — Haran dies before his father, Sarai is barren, Terah dies in Harran short of the destination (11:27–32). Against that dead end, Genesis 12:1–5 is structured as the answering beat: new creation by <em>blessing</em>. God chooses one family out of Babel's scattered nations and re-starts the melody — not with waters this time, but with a word.</p>
      <p>The vocabulary makes the connection explicit. The root <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">בָּרַךְ</span> (<em>barakh</em>, "bless") occurs five times in 12:2–3 — matching, as many readers have noticed, the five occurrences of "curse" in Genesis 1–11 (3:14, 17; 4:11; 5:29; 9:25). Where Babel's builders grasped at making "a name for ourselves," God promises to <em>make Abram's name great</em> — the name is given, not seized. And the horizon of the promise is exactly the scattered world of Genesis 10–11: "all the <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">מִשְׁפְּחֹת</span> (<em>mishpehot</em>, families/clans) of the ground" — the very word used for the dispersed peoples in the Table of Nations (10:5, 20, 31–32).</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Election is for mission.</strong>
        God narrows to one family precisely in order to widen to all families. Abraham is not chosen instead of the nations; he is chosen for the sake of the nations. Every later temptation to treat election as privilege rather than vocation — in Israel's story and the church's — is a misreading of Genesis 12.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         NEW ADAM
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="new-adam">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🌱</span> Abraham as New Adam</h2>
      <p>The promises to Abraham reissue the creation commission in covenant form. What God <em>commanded</em> Adam, God now <em>promises</em> to accomplish through Abraham — the grammar shifts from imperative to divine commitment, which is the whole theology of grace in miniature.</p>
      <table class="pattern-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Adam (Genesis 1–2)</th><th>Abraham (Genesis 12–22)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>"Be fruitful and multiply" (1:28)</td><td>"I will make you exceedingly fruitful… multiply you greatly" (17:2, 6)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>A garden planted for him, sacred space (2:8)</td><td>A land shown and promised to him (12:1, 7; 15:18)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Blessed by God (1:28)</td><td>Blessed to be a blessing (12:2–3)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Walks with God in the garden (3:8)</td><td>"Walk before me and be blameless" (17:1)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Seed promised to crush the serpent (3:15)</td><td>Seed promised, counted like the stars (15:5)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fails the test at the tree</td><td>Tested at Moriah — and trusts (22:1–18)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Abraham also behaves like a re-entering Adam. As he moves through Canaan he builds altars — at Shechem, Bethel, Hebron, Moriah — small outposts of worship where he "calls on the name of the LORD" (12:8; 13:4). In Creation 2.0 terms, he is planting flags of sacred space in de-created territory: not yet a temple, but the seed of one.</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> The narrowing-to-widen pattern established here becomes the Bible's standard operating procedure: one family for all families, one nation for all nations, one King for all kings, one Seed for all the seed (Gal 3:16, 29).</div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         COVENANT CUT
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="covenant-cut">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">📜</span> The Covenant Ceremonies</h2>
      <div class="word-study">
        <h4>Word Study: <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">בְּרִית</span> (berit) — "covenant"</h4>
        <p>Hebrew idiom does not "make" a covenant; it <em>cuts</em> one (<span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">כָּרַת בְּרִית</span>, <em>karat berit</em>) — language drawn from the ceremony in which animals were cut in two and the parties passed between the pieces, invoking the animals' fate on themselves if they broke faith (cf. Jer 34:18–19). A covenant is a bond of obligation sealed in life-and-death terms: family loyalty extended to a non-relative by oath.</p>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Genesis 15</strong> stages that ceremony with one staggering alteration. Abram prepares the animals and darkness falls — and then a smoking firepot and blazing torch, figures of God's own presence, pass between the pieces <em>alone</em> (15:17). Abram never walks. God takes both parties' obligations on Himself: the promise of seed and land will stand on divine faithfulness, not human performance. Verse 6 has already given the movement its soteriology in one line: "Abram believed the LORD, and he credited it to him as righteousness" — the verse Paul will place at the foundation of Romans 4 and Galatians 3.</p>
      <p><strong>Genesis 17</strong> then gives the covenant its shape in time. God identifies Himself as <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">אֵל שַׁדַּי</span> (<em>El Shaddai</em>), renames Abram "father of a multitude," and saturates the chapter with Genesis 1 verbs — "I will make you <em>exceedingly fruitful</em>… I will <em>multiply</em> you" (17:2, 6) — before adding the sign of circumcision: the covenant marked on the organ of generation, because the promise runs through the <em>seed</em>. Kings are promised (17:6, 16), quietly opening the door to Movement 5.</p>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> The one-sided pass-through of Genesis 15 anticipates the cross, where the covenant God again absorbs the curse of covenant-breaking in His own person (Gal 3:13–14) — so that "the blessing of Abraham might come to the Gentiles."</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE MOUNTAIN
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="testing">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">⛰️</span> Testing and the Mountain</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        "Take your son, your only son, whom you love — Isaac — and go to the region of Moriah."
        <span class="reference">Genesis 22:2</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Genesis 22 deliberately mirrors Genesis 12: the same <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">לֶךְ־לְךָ</span> ("go"), this time not <em>from</em> a past but <em>toward</em> an unthinkable future. Where Adam faced his test at a tree and grasped, Abraham faces his on a mountain and surrenders — trusting, as the narrative frames it, that "God himself will provide the lamb" (22:8). The angel's verdict makes the creational stakes explicit: because Abraham has not withheld his son, the blessing is confirmed on oath, the seed will be multiplied like stars and sand, will "possess the gate of his enemies," and "in your seed all the nations of the earth will be blessed" (22:16–18).</p>
      <p>The location matters for the rest of the story. "The mountain of the LORD" where provision replaced the son (22:14) is Moriah — the mount where, per 2 Chronicles 3:1, Solomon builds the Temple. The place of Abraham's test becomes the place of Israel's worship: sacred space founded on the memory that <em>God provides the substitute</em>.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>The faithful human, foreshadowed.</strong>
        Moriah is the first time in the Bible a human passes the Eden-style test. It is partial — Isaac walks away, the ram dies — but it sketches the shape of the answer to Movement 2's open question: a beloved only son, wood on his back, a mountain, and a God who provides.
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         A FAILING FAMILY
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="family">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">👣</span> The Promise Through a Failing Family</h2>
      <p>Genesis refuses to idealize its chosen family, and the honesty is theological. Abraham twice passes his wife off to foreign courts; Isaac repeats the trick; Jacob's very name means "heel-grabber," and he lives up to it; Judah sells a brother and solicits his own daughter-in-law. The carriers of the blessing behave, much of the time, like the world they were called to bless. Yet through every episode the narrative keeps score with one word: <em>barakh</em>. The blessing survives famine, deception, barrenness, and betrayal — because it rests on the God of Genesis 15, not on the family's performance.</p>
      <p>The Joseph story brings the movement to its designed conclusion. Sold into the empire of Egypt, Joseph becomes a channel of blessing <em>to the nations</em> — "all the world came to Egypt to buy grain" (41:57) — a first, ironic down payment on 12:3. His summary sentence gives Genesis its doctrine of providence: "You intended it for evil against me, but God intended it for good, to preserve many people alive" (50:20). And the book's final scene plants the seed of the next movement: Jacob's family in Egypt, where "the Israelites were fruitful and multiplied greatly… and the land was filled with them" (Exod 1:7) — Genesis 1:28 vocabulary, one verse before a Pharaoh arises who reads fruitfulness as threat.</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> Blessing → endangerment → preservation → multiplication. Four generations run the loop, and each time the promise survives by grace rather than merit. The covenant proves stronger than its carriers — the exact lesson Israel, and the church, will need.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         TRAJECTORY
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="forward">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🧭</span> Trajectory: Seed, Land, Blessing, Nations</h2>
      <p>Movement 3 leaves the creation project with four live wires, each carrying Eden's voltage forward:</p>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>Seed</h4><p>The line of Genesis 3:15 now runs through Isaac, Jacob, and — by Jacob's deathbed oracle — Judah, to whom "the obedience of the nations" belongs (49:10). Movements 5 and 7 will follow this wire to David and to Christ.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Land</h4><p>Promised, walked, and bought only in the size of a grave (Gen 23) — sacred space held by faith. Movement 4 turns the promise into a national inheritance; the prophets will widen it to a renewed earth.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Blessing</h4><p>Five blessings set against five curses; blessing that survives the family's failures. Paul will call the Spirit "the blessing of Abraham" reaching the Gentiles (Gal 3:14) — Movement 8's wire.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Nations</h4><p>The seventy scattered families of Genesis 10 remain the horizon. Their gathering begins at Pentecost and completes in the garden-city, where the tree's leaves heal the nations (Rev 22:2).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="pivot-box">
        <span class="pivot-label">Where the Story Goes Next</span>
        <p>Genesis ends with the covenant family fruitful — and enslavable — in Egypt. The question shifts from <em>who carries the promise?</em> to <em>how does a family become the "great nation" and "kingdom of priests" the promise requires?</em> Movement 4 answers with water, mountain, and glory: the Exodus as new creation.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="takeaway">Covenant is creation's rescue vehicle: God binding Himself, one-sidedly and on oath, to finish through Abraham's seed what Adam's race abandoned.</p>
    </section>

